<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870128-0010 </DOCNO><HL> Forstmann Little andamp; Co.Completes Its OfferFor Lear Siegler Shares</HL><DD> 01/28/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> LSITENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)AEROSPACE (ARO) </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Forstmann Little andamp; Co. said it completed its tender offer for all common and preferred shares of Lear Siegler Inc.    Forstmann Little, a closely held firm that specializes in leveraged buyouts, is acquiring Lear Siegler, a Santa Monica, Calif.-based concern with interests in aerospace, electronics and automotive products.    Forstmann Little said it received 98% of Lear Siegler's common shares and 84% of its preferred shares. Forstmann Little paid $92 a share for the common and $230 a share for the preferred, for a total of about $1.66 billion. The total acquisition cost of $2.1 billion includes refinancing of Lear Siegler debt and certain fees.    In a leveraged buyout, the assets of the acquired company are used as collateral for loans to finance the transaction. Earnings and asset sales are used to service and retire the debt. </TEXT></DOC>